<Chapter Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.div.1">
<Title>Shadow Administration</Title>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.1">
<Primary>shadows</Primary>
<Secondary>administration</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<!--.so gd/screen.mac-->
<!--.nh
-->
<Para>Shadow administration allows an administrator to manage shadows
and shadowing jobs.  Administrators can manage shadows and shadowing
jobs only for those master object entries for which they are
responsible.  Shadow administration can be performed only when a
bind has been made to the local DSA.
</Para>
<Para>This chapter describes the shadow administration operations and
interface.  It shows all the masks that are used, their meanings, and
input options.  It also describes each of the shadow
administration operations and the associated mask sequences.
</Para>
<Para>Using shadow administration operations an administrator can
</Para>
<ItemizedList>
<ListItem>
<Para>Create shadows of master entries on remote DSAs
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>Create shadowing jobs to update shadows
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>Change the update frequency of a shadowing job
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>Remove shadows and shadowing jobs
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>Display existing shadowing jobs
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>Display detailed information about errors that occurred during a shadow update
</Para>
</ListItem>
</ItemizedList>
<Sect1 Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.div.2">
<Title>Creating Shadows of Master Entries on Remote DSAs</Title>
<Para>The unit of shadow creation on a target (remote) DSA can be either a single object or a subtree.
</Para>
<Para>An administrator creates shadows on different DSAs to increase the
availability of the data and reduce network access time and
communication costs.  A temporary inconsistency between master and
shadow entries is tolerated by directory applications.  If this
inconsistency is not acceptable, only master information should be
requested by a directory application.
</Para>
</Sect1>
<Sect1 Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.div.3">
<Title>Creating Shadowing Jobs</Title>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.2">
<Primary>shadowing jobs</Primary>
<Secondary>creating</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<Para>A shadowing job updates shadows of master entries.  A shadowing job consists
of the following:
</Para>
<ItemizedList>
<ListItem>
<Para>An object name and its interpretation (single object or subtree) for the object
whose shadows should be updated
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>The name of the target DSA where the shadows are present
</Para>
</ListItem>
<ListItem>
<Para>The update frequency that specifies how often the daemon process updating the shadows must be run
</Para>
</ListItem>
</ItemizedList>
<Para>An administrator should select a high frequency for updates when
master entries change frequently (for example, every 10 minutes) and
the shadows must be updated as soon as possible.  An administrator
should select a low frequency for updates when the master entries
change less frequently (for example, once a week).  A medium frequency
should be selected when the frequency of updates required falls somewhere
between high and low.
</Para>
<Para>Shadowing jobs can be created for shadows that have not been created
by shadow administration.  An inactive shadowing job can be
created that can be activated later by the <Literal>Update Shadowing Job</Literal>
operation.  Shadowing is initiated by the master entries, so shadowing
jobs only need to be created for subtrees or objects that are mastered
by the bind DSA.
</Para>
</Sect1>
<Sect1 Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.div.4">
<Title>Removing Shadows and Shadowing Jobs</Title>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.3">
<Primary>shadowing jobs</Primary>
<Secondary>removing</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.4">
<Primary>shadows</Primary>
<Secondary>removing</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<Para>Shadows can be removed from remote DSAs when they are no longer required.
The associated shadowing job is automatically removed from the local DSA.
</Para>
<Para>A shadowing job can be removed without removing the shadows.  This
should only be done by an administrator when shadows have been removed
by some other means such as subtree administration operations.
</Para>
</Sect1>
<Sect1 Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.div.5">
<Title>Displaying Shadowing Jobs and Error Information</Title>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.5">
<Primary>shadowing jobs</Primary>
<Secondary>viewing list of</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.6">
<Primary>shadowing jobs</Primary>
<Secondary>error information</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<Para>An administrator can display the list of existing shadowing jobs by using
Masks 14g through 14j and can display errors that occurred during shadow updates by
using Mask 15.
</Para>
</Sect1>
<Sect1 Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.div.6">
<Title>Mask 2: DSA Identification</Title>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.7">
<Primary>Directory System Agents (DSAs)</Primary>
<Secondary>managing shadows (mask 2)</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<IndexTerm Id="OSFGDS.GDSSHA.indx.8">
<Primary>masks</Primary>
<Secondary>identifying DSAs (2)</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<Para>Mask 2 (Figure 10-1) is used to specify the DSA in which the shadows are to be managed.
</Para>
<?sml-need 4.0i>
<?sml-indent 0>
